      "text": "The **Security.evtx** file is the Windows Security Event Log, which records audit data such as logon attempts, privilege use, and policy changes. It is one of the most important files in digital forensics and incident response (DFIR).\n\nSince you mentioned the filename, you are likely looking to investigate suspicious activity on a system. Here is a breakdown of how to analyze this file and what specific \"red flags\" to look for.\n\n### 1. Critical Event IDs to Monitor\nIf you are threat hunting, these are the most important IDs to filter for:\n\n| Event ID | Description | Why it matters |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **4624** | Successful Logon | Shows who accessed the system. Check the **Logon Type** (Type 3 \u003d Network, Type 10 \u003d RDP). |\n| **4625** | Failed Logon | High counts often indicate brute-force or password-spraying attacks. |\n| **4672** | Special Privileges | Assigned to a new logon (e.g., an Admin logged in). Often paired with 4624. |\n| **4688** | New Process Created | Tracks command-line execution (if \"Audit Process Creation\" is enabled). |\n| **4720** | User Created | Sudden creation of a new user account is a common persistence technique. |\n| **1102** | Log Cleared | A major red flag; attackers clear logs to hide their tracks. |\n| **4697** | Service Installed | Often triggered by tools like **PsExec** during lateral movement. |\n\n---\n\n### 2. Advanced Threat Hunting Scenarios\nBeyond basic logins, look for these specific patterns that indicate a breach:\n\n*   **Pass-the-Hash (PtH):**\n    *   Look for **Event ID 4624** with **Logon Type 3** (Network) and an Authentication Package of **NTLM**.\n    *   Specifically, check if the \"Key Length\" is **0**, which is a common indicator of a PtH attack.\n*   **Kerberoasting (on Domain Controllers):**\n    *   Filter for **Event ID 4769** (Service Ticket Requested).\n    *   Watch for encryption type **0x17** (RC4-HMAC), which is weaker and targeted for offline cracking, or a sudden spike in requests for different service accounts from a single user.\n*   **Lateral Movement:**\n    *   **Event ID 4648:** A logon was attempted using explicit credentials (common when an attacker uses `runas` or a stolen password to access a network share).\n    *   **Event ID 5140:** A network share was accessed. Look for access to `C$` or `ADMIN$` shares.\n\n---\n\n### 3. How to Analyze the File\nIf you have the `.evtx` file and want to parse it, you can use these tools:\n\n#### A. PowerShell (Built-in)\nIf you are on a Windows machine, you can query the file directly without \"installing\" it to your system log:\n```powershell\n# Get the 20 most recent successful logons from a specific file\nGet-WinEvent -Path \"C:\\path\\to\\Security.evtx\" -FilterHashtable @{Id\u003d4624} -MaxEvents 20\n```\n\n#### B. EvtxECmd (Recommended for Forensics)\nCreated by Eric Zimmerman, **EvtxECmd** is the gold standard for parsing logs into a CSV for analysis in Excel or Timeline Explorer.\n```bash\nEvtxECmd.exe -f \"Security.evtx\" --csv \"C:\\Analysis\" --csvf \"security_audit.csv\"\n```\n\n#### C. Hayabusa / Chainsaw\nThese are \"Sigma-based\" threat hunting tools. They automatically scan your `.evtx` file against thousands of known hacking techniques and give you a summary of \"High\" or \"Critical\" alerts.\n\n---\n\n### Next Steps\nIf you have a specific entry you\u0027re confused about, you can **copy and paste the XML view** of the event here (masking any sensitive usernames or IPs), and I can help you interpret what happened. \n\n**Are you investigating a specific incident (e.g., suspected ransomware or unauthorized access)?**",
