      "parts": [{
        "text": "The **Security.evtx** file is the Windows"
      }, {
        "text": " Security Event Log, which records audit data such as logon attempts, privilege use, and policy changes. It is one of the"
      }, {
        "text": " most important files in digital forensics and incident response (DFIR).\n\nSince you mentioned the filename, you are likely looking to"
      }, {
        "text": " investigate suspicious activity on a system. Here is a breakdown of how to analyze this file and what specific \"red flags\""
      }, {
        "text": " to look for.\n\n### 1. Critical Event IDs to Monitor\nIf you are threat hunting, these are the"
      }, {
        "text": " most important IDs to filter for:\n\n| Event ID | Description | Why it matters |\n| :--- | :--- | :"
      }, {
        "text": "--- |\n| **4624** | Successful Logon | Shows who accessed the system. Check the **Logon Type"
      }, {
        "text": "** (Type 3 \u003d Network, Type 10 \u003d RDP). |\n| **4625** |"
      }, {
        "text": " Failed Logon | High counts often indicate brute-force or password-spraying attacks. |\n| **4672"
